PAIRS = [
# ── ANTI_DUMPING (20 pairs) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"Which countries are subject to anti-dumping investigation on electrogalvanized steel imports into India?","chosen":"According to the DGTR initiation notice, Korea RP, Japan, and Singapore are the three countries subject to the anti-dumping investigation on imports of electrogalvanized steel into India. The investigation was initiated following a petition by the domestic industry alleging material injury.","rejected":"Several Asian countries may be subject to anti-dumping investigation on electrogalvanized steel imports. The exact countries depend on the specific investigation."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What products are covered under the anti-dumping investigation on seamless tubes from China?","chosen":"The anti-dumping investigation covers seamless tubes, pipes, and hollow profiles of iron, alloy or non-alloy steel originating in or exported from China PR, as specified in the DGTR initiation notification. This includes products under HS codes 7304.","rejected":"The investigation covers various steel tube products from China. Different types of pipes and tubes may be included."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the difference between an anti-dumping duty and a countervailing duty?","chosen":"An anti-dumping duty (ADD) is imposed when imported goods are sold below their normal value (dumped), causing material injury to the domestic industry. A countervailing duty (CVD) is imposed when imports benefit from government subsidies in the exporting country. Both are WTO-compliant trade remedies governed by separate agreements — the Anti-Dumping Agreement and the SCM Agreement.","rejected":"Anti-dumping and countervailing duties are both import duties used to protect domestic industries from unfair trade practices."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What must a domestic industry demonstrate to initiate an anti-dumping investigation?","chosen":"To initiate an investigation, the domestic industry must file a written petition with DGTR demonstrating: (1) evidence of dumping — imports sold below normal value; (2) material injury or threat thereof; and (3) a causal link. The petitioner must represent at least 25% of domestic production by volume.","rejected":"The domestic industry files a complaint with the government showing that imports are causing harm to domestic producers."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"How long can an anti-dumping duty remain in force in India?","chosen":"Under WTO Article 11 and Indian AD law, an anti-dumping duty can remain in force for a maximum of 5 years. It may be extended for a further 5 years after a sunset review if DGTR determines that expiry would likely lead to continuation or recurrence of dumping and injury.","rejected":"Anti-dumping duties can be maintained for several years. The government decides when to remove them based on market conditions."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the PCN methodology in anti-dumping investigations?","chosen":"PCN (Product Control Number) is a systematic classification methodology that encodes product characteristics — grade, thickness, width, surface treatment — so that like-for-like price comparisons can be made between imported and domestically produced goods. It prevents averaging across dissimilar grades that would distort the dumping margin calculation.","rejected":"PCN is a code used to classify products in anti-dumping investigations for price comparison purposes."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the normal value in an anti-dumping investigation?","chosen":"Normal value is the comparable price of the like product sold in the domestic market of the exporting country. If domestic sales are insufficient (below 5% of export volume) or distorted, DGTR may construct normal value using cost of production plus reasonable amounts for SGA costs and profits, as provided in WTO Anti-Dumping Agreement Article 2.","rejected":"Normal value is the price at which products are sold in the exporting country's domestic market."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is a sunset review in the context of anti-dumping duties?","chosen":"A sunset review is conducted before the 5-year expiry of an anti-dumping duty to determine whether expiry would likely lead to continuation or recurrence of dumping and injury. Required under WTO Article 11.3. If DGTR concludes injury would recur, the duty is extended for another 5 years.","rejected":"A sunset review examines whether anti-dumping duties should continue. It looks at current market conditions to decide."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"How is the dumping margin calculated?","chosen":"Dumping margin = (Normal Value - Export Price) / Export Price, expressed as a percentage. DGTR uses the weighted average normal value compared to the weighted average export price across all transactions during the investigation period. If the margin is de minimis (below 2%), no duty is imposed.","rejected":"The dumping margin is the difference between the price in the exporting country and the export price to India."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is material injury in anti-dumping law?","chosen":"Material injury is assessed by examining factors including: volume of dumped imports, effect on domestic prices (price undercutting, suppression, depression), and consequent impact on the domestic industry (decline in production, sales, market share, profits, employment, capacity utilisation). A single factor is not conclusive — all relevant factors must be examined.","rejected":"Material injury means that domestic industry is being harmed by dumped imports. The government investigates to determine if harm is significant."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the injury margin and how does it relate to the duty imposed?","chosen":"The injury margin is the amount by which the export price must be raised to eliminate the injury to the domestic industry (i.e., the difference between cost of production plus reasonable profit of the domestic industry and the import price). The anti-dumping duty imposed is the lesser of the dumping margin and the injury margin — this is the lesser duty rule applied in India.","rejected":"The injury margin helps determine how much duty to impose. The duty is set to address the harm caused by dumped imports."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What are the key grounds for challenging an anti-dumping duty at CESTAT?","chosen":"Parties may challenge AD duties at CESTAT (Customs Excise and Service Tax Appellate Tribunal) on grounds including: incorrect normal value calculation, errors in export price determination, failure to apply lesser duty rule, procedural defects in the investigation, or inconsistency with WTO Anti-Dumping Agreement obligations. CESTAT has jurisdiction over disputes on imposition, modification, or revocation of AD duties.","rejected":"Anti-dumping duties can be challenged legally on various grounds related to the investigation process and calculations."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"How does India treat related-party transactions in anti-dumping investigations?","chosen":"When the exporter and importer are related (e.g., parent-subsidiary), DGTR adjusts the export price to a constructed export price based on the resale price to the first independent buyer, less selling expenses and a reasonable profit margin. This prevents artificially low transfer prices from understating the export price and inflating the dumping margin.","rejected":"Related-party transactions may be treated differently in anti-dumping investigations. The government adjusts prices to ensure fair comparison."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the role of the designated authority in India's anti-dumping framework?","chosen":"The Designated Authority (DA) is the officer within DGTR appointed to conduct anti-dumping investigations. The DA examines petitions, issues public notices, conducts hearings, performs on-site verification of data in exporting countries, and submits final findings to the Ministry of Finance, which issues the duty notification. The DA's findings are final subject to CESTAT and High Court review.","rejected":"The designated authority is a government official who oversees anti-dumping investigations in India."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What are the five countries in the anti-dumping investigation on flat rolled products of stainless steel?","chosen":"According to the DGTR investigation records, the anti-dumping investigation on flat rolled products of stainless steel names 15 countries: China PR, Korea RP, European Union, Japan, Taiwan, Indonesia, USA, Thailand, South Africa, UAE, Hong Kong, Singapore, and others. The investigation covers multiple origins simultaneously given the global nature of stainless steel trade.","rejected":"The investigation covers several countries that export stainless steel to India. Multiple Asian and European countries are included."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is a circumvention investigation in anti-dumping?","chosen":"A circumvention investigation examines whether exporters are routing products through third countries or making minor modifications to avoid paying anti-dumping duties. For example, if China faces AD duties on HR coils, a circumvention investigation would examine whether Chinese coils are being processed in Vietnam and exported as Vietnamese-origin to India. If circumvention is found, the duty is extended to cover the circumventing country or process.","rejected":"A circumvention investigation looks at whether companies are trying to avoid anti-dumping duties through indirect methods."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"How does the confidentiality regime work in DGTR investigations?","chosen":"DGTR investigations have two tracks: confidential and non-confidential. Parties may claim confidentiality for commercially sensitive information (cost data, customer lists) and must submit a non-confidential summary. Other parties have the right to inspect non-confidential summaries. If a party claims confidentiality without justification, DGTR may disregard the information. The principle of interested party participation requires that all parties have meaningful access to the case record.","rejected":"DGTR investigations allow parties to keep sensitive business information confidential while sharing non-sensitive information with other parties."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the WTO dispute on Section 232 US steel tariffs filed by India?","chosen":"India filed WTO dispute DS547 against the United States challenging Section 232 steel tariffs (25%) as inconsistent with GATT Articles II and XIX and the WTO Safeguard Agreement. The WTO panel found in India's favour in 2022, ruling that Section 232 measures are safeguard measures that must comply with WTO safeguard disciplines (not unilateral national security exemptions). The US appealed, leaving the dispute in limbo due to the non-functioning Appellate Body.","rejected":"India has challenged US steel tariffs at the WTO. The dispute concerns whether the tariffs are consistent with WTO trade rules."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"How are new shippers treated in existing anti-dumping duty orders?","chosen":"A new shipper review allows exporters who did not export to India during the original investigation period to request an individual dumping margin determination. During the review, the exporter may apply for a suspension of duty collection on a security basis. If the review finds a lower individual margin, the duty is reduced accordingly. This prevents exporters who are not actually dumping from being caught by duties set for other exporters.","rejected":"New exporters who were not part of the original investigation can apply for a review to get their own duty rate determined."},
{"domain":"ANTI_DUMPING","question":"What is the lesser duty rule applied in India's anti-dumping regime?","chosen":"India applies the lesser duty rule: the anti-dumping duty imposed is limited to the lesser of (a) the dumping margin (normal value minus export price) or (b) the injury margin (the price increase needed to eliminate the injury to domestic industry). This is consistent with WTO Article 9.1, which recommends — but does not require — the lesser duty rule. India's application of this rule limits the protective effect compared to countries that impose the full dumping margin.","rejected":"India's anti-dumping system has a rule that limits the duty to what is necessary to address the harm. This prevents excessive protection."},
# ── SAFEGUARD (10 pairs) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What triggers the initiation of a safeguard investigation in India?","chosen":"A safeguard investigation is initiated when DGTR receives a petition from the domestic industry providing evidence of: (1) an absolute or relative surge in imports; (2) serious injury or threat thereof; and (3) a causal link. Unlike anti-dumping, safeguard measures apply to imports from all countries — they are non-discriminatory MFN measures.","rejected":"A safeguard investigation starts when there is evidence that imports are harming domestic industry. The government investigates and may impose duties."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What type of products are covered by the safeguard investigation on steel flat products?","chosen":"The safeguard investigation covers imports of Non-Alloy and Alloy Steel Flat Products into India, as specified in the DGTR initiation notification. This includes hot-rolled and cold-rolled flat steel in coil and non-coil form falling under relevant HS chapters.","rejected":"The safeguard investigation covers flat steel products imported into India."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"How is safeguard different from anti-dumping in terms of country coverage and injury threshold?","chosen":"Safeguard measures are MFN — they apply to all WTO members simultaneously. Anti-dumping targets specific exporting countries. Additionally, safeguard requires a higher injury threshold (serious injury, meaning significant impairment of the domestic industry's position) versus anti-dumping's material injury (measurable harm). Developing country exports below 3% market share are typically excluded from safeguard measures under WTO rules.","rejected":"Safeguard and anti-dumping are different trade remedies. Safeguard applies more broadly while anti-dumping targets specific countries."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What is the maximum duration for provisional safeguard measures in India?","chosen":"Provisional safeguard measures in India can be applied for a maximum of 200 days under the Customs Tariff Act 1975 (Section 8B). These are imposed when there is clear evidence of injury and the domestic industry needs immediate relief. If the final investigation does not find serious injury, duties collected provisionally must be refunded.","rejected":"Provisional safeguard measures can be applied temporarily for a limited period while investigation continues."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What is the WTO Safeguard Agreement requirement on compensation?","chosen":"Under WTO Safeguard Agreement Article 8, a country applying safeguard measures must offer compensatory concessions (e.g., tariff reductions on other goods) to exporting countries suffering trade diversion. If no agreement is reached, affected exporters may retaliate with equivalent trade concessions after 3 years. This compensation obligation is a key constraint on the use of safeguard measures.","rejected":"Countries applying safeguard measures may need to compensate affected exporters under WTO rules."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"How has India used safeguard measures on steel historically?","chosen":"India imposed a 25% safeguard duty on hot-rolled flat products of non-alloy and alloy steel for 200 days in 2016 (extended in various forms). The measure was challenged by China and Korea at the WTO (DS518, DS546). The WTO panel found several aspects of India's measure inconsistent with the Safeguard Agreement, particularly the parallel application of safeguard and anti-dumping measures on the same product category.","rejected":"India has used safeguard measures on steel imports in the past. These measures were aimed at protecting the domestic steel industry."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What is absolute vs relative surge in the context of safeguard investigations?","chosen":"An absolute surge means the volume of imports has increased in absolute terms over the investigation period. A relative surge means imports have increased relative to domestic production (import penetration has risen) even if absolute volumes have not. WTO rules permit safeguard investigations based on either form of surge, but the trend must be sufficiently recent, sudden, and sharp.","rejected":"Safeguard investigations look at whether imports have increased significantly. The increase can be measured in different ways."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What developing country exemptions apply under the WTO Safeguard Agreement?","chosen":"Under WTO Safeguard Agreement Article 9.1, safeguard measures shall not be applied against imports from a developing country WTO member as long as that country's share of imports does not exceed 3%, and collectively developing countries with sub-3% shares do not account for more than 9% of total imports. This provides meaningful protection for small developing country exporters.","rejected":"Developing countries may be exempt from certain safeguard measures under WTO rules if their export share is small."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"Can safeguard and anti-dumping measures apply simultaneously to the same product?","chosen":"The simultaneous application of safeguard and anti-dumping measures on the same product from the same country raises WTO compatibility concerns — the WTO panel in DS518 found India's parallel application inconsistent with Article 2.2 of the Safeguard Agreement. The general principle is that safeguard measures address global import surges while anti-dumping addresses country-specific dumping; applying both doubles the protective burden.","rejected":"Applying both safeguard and anti-dumping measures to the same product may raise legal issues under WTO rules."},
{"domain":"SAFEGUARD","question":"What is the injury determination process in a safeguard investigation?","chosen":"DGTR evaluates all relevant factors: (1) absolute and relative increase in imports; (2) share of the domestic market taken by increased imports; (3) changes in domestic production, sales, productivity, capacity utilisation, profits and losses, employment; (4) whether injury is attributable to imports versus other factors (non-attribution requirement). A full hearing where domestic industry, importers, and foreign exporters present evidence is mandatory.","rejected":"The injury determination process involves examining how imports have affected the domestic industry across multiple economic indicators."},
# ── RAW_MATERIAL (10 pairs) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"What is India's coking coal import dependency?","chosen":"India imports approximately 85% of its coking coal requirements from Australia and the USA. This dependency creates direct supply chain risk: Australian port disruptions, weather events, or export restrictions propagate to Indian blast furnace operations within the typical 45–60 day inventory buffer maintained by integrated mills.","rejected":"India depends heavily on imported coking coal for steelmaking. Most imports come from a few key countries."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"How does iron ore availability affect Indian steel competitiveness?","chosen":"India has approximately 33 billion tonnes of iron ore reserves and is self-sufficient, giving it a cost advantage over import-dependent Japan, Korea, and Taiwan. Odisha and Karnataka are the primary mining states. However, beneficiation capacity for low-grade ores (below 58% Fe) is a bottleneck, and NMDC's export restrictions have historically limited revenue optimisation from surplus ores.","rejected":"India has significant domestic iron ore reserves which helps reduce costs for steel production compared to other countries."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"What is the impact of scrap steel prices on India's EAF-based producers?","chosen":"Electric arc furnace producers (approximately 30% of Indian steel output) are directly exposed to scrap price volatility. India imports 6–8 million tonnes of scrap annually — primarily from the Middle East, USA, and Europe. When Chinese scrap restrictions tighten or EU end-of-life vehicle scrap regulations reduce export availability, Indian EAF producers face input cost pressure of $20–40/tonne that BF-BOF producers are insulated from.","rejected":"Scrap prices affect certain Indian steel producers who use electric arc furnaces. Higher scrap prices increase their production costs."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"How does the coking coal price index affect steel production costs?","chosen":"Coking coal accounts for approximately 35–40% of BF-BOF steel production costs in India. The HCC (hard coking coal) benchmark, set quarterly through Australian contract negotiations, directly determines input costs. When HCC moves from $200/tonne to $300/tonne (as occurred during the 2022 energy shock), variable production costs for Indian integrated mills increase by approximately Rs 1,500–2,000/tonne, equivalent to 5–7% of hot metal costs.","rejected":"Coking coal prices have a significant impact on steel production costs. When coal prices rise, steel becomes more expensive to produce."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"What alternatives to Australian coking coal is India pursuing?","chosen":"India is pursuing diversification through: (1) Mozambique's Tete Basin (Tata Steel's Benga mine); (2) Canadian British Columbia coking coal; (3) Mongolian coking coal via rail linkages. Additionally, JSW Steel and NMDC Steel have piloted partial substitution with non-coking coal + direct reduced iron (DRI) routes to reduce dependency. Government-to-government agreements with Russia have also increased Russian coking coal imports post-2022 sanctions.","rejected":"India is working to reduce dependence on Australian coking coal by exploring alternative sources from other countries."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"What is the role of pellets in India's steelmaking value chain?","chosen":"Iron ore pellets are the beneficiated, high-grade (63–67% Fe) feedstock for DRI/sponge iron production — a critical input for India's EAF and BF routes. India is the world's largest DRI producer. Pellet plants (primarily in Odisha, Goa) process low-grade fines into export-grade pellets. The domestic pellet market is linked to gas prices (for DR-grade pellets) and coal prices (for BF-grade pellets).","rejected":"Pellets are an important input material in steel production. They are produced from iron ore fines and used in various steelmaking processes."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"How does China's restriction on steel scrap exports affect India?","chosen":"When China restricts scrap steel exports (as it did in 2021 to prioritise domestic EAF capacity), global scrap supply tightens and prices rise. For Indian EAF producers who import scrap, this represents a direct cost increase. Conversely, when Chinese domestic scrap supply loosens and they become net exporters, global scrap prices fall — reducing Indian EAF input costs. India's proximity to Middle Eastern scrap markets provides a partial buffer.","rejected":"China's scrap restrictions affect global scrap supply and prices, which impacts Indian steelmakers who use scrap as input."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"What is the significance of NMDC in India's iron ore supply chain?","chosen":"NMDC (National Mineral Development Corporation) is India's largest iron ore producer, accounting for approximately 35–40 million tonnes per annum of production from Chhattisgarh and Karnataka. As a government-owned entity, NMDC's price notifications effectively set the floor for domestic iron ore pricing. Its production disruptions (mining restrictions in Bailadila, Karnataka forest clearances) directly impact feedstock availability for BF-BOF mills in central and southern India.","rejected":"NMDC is an important government-owned iron ore producer in India that supplies a significant portion of domestic steel industry requirements."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"How does logistics affect India's raw material costs for steelmaking?","chosen":"India's inland freight costs for raw materials are disproportionately high compared to coastal economies. Rail freight for iron ore from Odisha to inland steel plants in Jharkhand or Chhattisgarh adds Rs 800–1,200/tonne to delivered costs. Port congestion at Paradip and Visakhapatnam during monsoon season delays coking coal receipt, forcing mills to maintain higher safety stock. Dedicated freight corridor completion (Eastern DFC) is expected to reduce raw material logistics costs by 15–20%.","rejected":"Logistics costs for transporting raw materials affect the overall cost competitiveness of Indian steel producers."},
{"domain":"RAW_MATERIAL","question":"What is the role of DRI in India's steelmaking and how does it link to gas prices?","chosen":"Direct Reduced Iron (DRI) is produced by reducing iron ore using natural gas (gas-based DRI, MIDREX/HYL process) or coal (coal-based DRI, rotary kiln). India is the world's largest DRI producer at ~42 million tonnes annually. Gas-based DRI has significantly lower carbon intensity (~0.9 tCO₂/t DRI) versus coal-based (~3.0 tCO₂/t). When natural gas prices spiked post-2022, gas-based DRI became uneconomical, shifting production to coal-based routes and increasing India's overall steel sector emissions intensity.","rejected":"DRI is a type of iron used in steelmaking that is produced by reducing iron ore. Different production methods use different fuels."},
# ── POLICY_OPPORTUNITY (10 pairs) ────────────────────────────────────────────
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"How does India-UAE CEPA benefit Indian steel exporters?","chosen":"The India-UAE CEPA (effective May 2022) provides zero-duty access for Indian flat steel products to the UAE — versus the standard 5% MFN tariff. The UAE's role as a re-export hub gives CEPA-covered Indian steel access to GCC markets (Saudi Arabia, Oman, Qatar, Kuwait). India-UAE steel trade reached approximately $1.2 billion in FY2024, up from $0.8 billion pre-CEPA.","rejected":"India-UAE CEPA provides trade benefits including reduced tariffs, helping Indian steel exporters access UAE and Gulf markets."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"What is the PLI scheme for specialty steel?","chosen":"The PLI scheme for specialty steel (launched FY2022-23, outlay Rs 6,322 crore over 5 years) targets 25 MT of specialty steel production by FY2026-27 across five product lines: coated/plated steel, high-strength steel, specialty rails, alloy steel bars, and electrical steel. Incentives range from 4–12% of incremental sales. Actual disbursements through FY2025 are approximately Rs 1,900 crore — 30% utilisation — primarily due to quality certification bottlenecks.","rejected":"India's PLI scheme for specialty steel provides financial incentives to producers of high-value steel products."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"How does India's FTP 2023 support steel sector exports?","chosen":"FTP 2023 designates Mandi Gobindgarh and Raipur as Towns of Export Excellence for steel, unlocking priority credit, common infrastructure funding, and export facilitation services. The advance authorisation scheme for duty-free steel input imports tied to export obligations was streamlined with digital processing. The EPCG scheme allows duty-free import of capital equipment for steel processing lines against a 6× export obligation over 6 years.","rejected":"India's FTP 2023 has provisions that support steel exports including special designations and incentive schemes."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"What is India's target for steel production capacity by 2030?","chosen":"The National Steel Policy 2017 targets 300 million tonnes of steel production capacity and 255 MT of consumption by FY2030-31. India's current capacity is approximately 175 MT. Achieving the target requires approximately 125 MT of incremental capacity addition — roughly the current capacity of the entire EU steel industry — implying investment of Rs 10–12 lakh crore over the decade.","rejected":"India has ambitious targets for steel production growth. The government aims to significantly increase capacity by 2030."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"How can India leverage the EU CBAM for competitive advantage?","chosen":"Indian mills that invest in decarbonisation to demonstrate embedded emissions below the EU CBAM benchmark (~1.328 tCO₂/t for steel) would pay zero CBAM levy — gaining a competitive advantage over Chinese BF-BOF exports (~2.1 tCO₂/t). Tata Steel Jamshedpur and JSW Vijayanagar are closest to this threshold. A government-backed green steel certification scheme would facilitate EU market positioning and command a 5–10% price premium from European automotive OEMs committed to Scope 3 emission reduction.","rejected":"India can gain competitive advantage under CBAM by reducing the carbon intensity of steel production."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"What FTA negotiations are relevant for India's steel export strategy?","chosen":"Key ongoing FTA negotiations affecting steel: (1) India-EU FTA — under negotiation, EU is India's second-largest steel market; CBAM creates urgency to secure market access with concurrent decarbonisation commitments; (2) India-UK FTA — concluded but ratification pending; covers steel tariff elimination over 7 years; (3) India-GCC FTA — negotiations ongoing, GCC is a major steel re-export hub; (4) India-Canada FTA (paused) — covers coking coal supply security as a quid pro quo.","rejected":"India is negotiating several FTAs that could benefit steel exports by reducing tariffs in key markets."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"What is the significance of BIS Quality Control Orders for import substitution?","chosen":"BIS Quality Control Orders (QCOs) mandate that domestic and imported steel products must carry BIS Standard Marks before sale. For imports, this requires Foreign Manufacturer Certification Scheme (FMCS) registration — a process taking 3–6 months and involving factory audit in the exporting country. QCOs covering IS 2062 (structural steel), IS 1079 (HR plates), and IS 513 (CR sheets) effectively create a non-tariff barrier that deters low-quality imports while protecting compliant suppliers.","rejected":"BIS Quality Control Orders require steel products to meet quality standards. This helps protect consumers and supports import substitution."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"How does the National Green Hydrogen Mission interact with steel sector decarbonisation?","chosen":"India's National Green Hydrogen Mission (target: 5 MT green H₂ by 2030) explicitly identifies steel as a priority end-use sector. DRI-EAF using green hydrogen (H₂-DRI) reduces steel sector emissions to approximately 0.1–0.3 tCO₂/t — well below the CBAM benchmark. JSW Steel and SAIL have announced pilot H₂-DRI projects. At green hydrogen costs below $2/kg (expected post-2030), H₂-DRI becomes cost-competitive with coal-based BF-BOF in India.","rejected":"India's green hydrogen mission could support steel sector decarbonisation by providing clean fuel for direct reduction processes."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"What is the significance of India's export to Southeast Asia for flat steel?","chosen":"Southeast Asia absorbs approximately 18 million tonnes of flat steel annually — historically dominated by Chinese suppliers. Under India's ASEAN FTA (AIFTA), Indian HR coil enters Vietnam, Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, and Philippines at zero or near-zero duty. India's current export penetration is below 6% of ASEAN flat product demand, constrained by logistics costs, specification gaps, and limited L/C facility availability for MSME traders. Closing these gaps unlocks a $3–4 billion addressable market.","rejected":"Southeast Asia is an important potential market for Indian flat steel exports. India's FTA with ASEAN provides tariff advantages."},
{"domain":"POLICY_OPPORTUNITY","question":"What policy measures can reduce India's steel import dependence?","chosen":"Key measures to reduce import dependence: (1) PLI utilisation acceleration — address quality certification bottlenecks for specialty steel; (2) BIS QCO expansion — extend quality orders to additional flat product categories; (3) AD duty calibration — maintain where dumping persists, reduce where injury basis has weakened post-China restructuring; (4) Coking coal diversification — government offtake agreements for non-Australian sources; (5) H₂-DRI pilot subsidisation — reduce early mover risk for decarbonised production.","rejected":"Several policy measures can help reduce India's dependence on steel imports including tariff and non-tariff measures."},
# ── CBAM_COMPLIANCE (10 pairs) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"What are the EU CBAM reporting obligations for Indian steel exporters?","chosen":"Under EU CBAM (Regulation 2023/956), Indian steel exporters must report embedded direct and indirect emissions per tonne exported to the EU. Transitional phase (October 2023 – December 2025): quarterly reports only, no payment. From January 2026: CBAM certificates must be purchased for the embedded carbon gap versus the EU ETS price. CN codes covered include 7206–7229 and selected 7301–7326 articles.","rejected":"Indian steel exporters must report carbon emissions under CBAM. There are reporting requirements and potential financial obligations."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"How is the CBAM levy calculated for Indian steel?","chosen":"CBAM levy per tonne = (embedded emissions tCO₂/t) × (EU ETS price €/tCO₂) minus any verified carbon price paid in India. Indian BF-BOF steel averages ~2.4 tCO₂/t versus the EU benchmark 1.328 tCO₂/t. At €70/tCO₂ ETS price, the implied gross liability is ~€168/t, less any Indian carbon pricing credit. India has no operative carbon price, so the full levy applies.","rejected":"The CBAM levy is based on carbon content and EU carbon prices. Indian steel exporters will need to pay based on their emissions."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"What is the EU ETS benchmark emission intensity for steel?","chosen":"The EU default embedded emission value for steel under CBAM methodology is approximately 1.328 tCO₂ per tonne for BF-BOF production. Exporters demonstrating actual emissions below this through ISO 14064-verified reporting pay reduced or zero CBAM levy. The benchmark reflects best-practice BF-BOF technology; H₂-DRI routes produce 0.1–0.3 tCO₂/t, well below the threshold.","rejected":"The EU has set a benchmark for steel emissions under CBAM. Steel produced with lower emissions may pay less."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"Which Indian steel facilities are closest to CBAM compliance without levy?","chosen":"Tata Steel Jamshedpur (most energy-efficient Indian integrated mill, estimated 2.1–2.2 tCO₂/t after recent investments) and JSW Steel Vijayanagar (2.2–2.3 tCO₂/t, coastal location, scrap co-processing) are closest to the 1.328 tCO₂/t CBAM benchmark. SAIL's older inland plants (2.5–2.7 tCO₂/t) face the largest gap and would require BF modernisation or BOF-to-EAF conversion to approach compliance without levy.","rejected":"Some Indian steel plants with more modern and efficient production are better positioned for CBAM compliance."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"What verification requirements does CBAM impose on Indian exporters?","chosen":"CBAM requires that embedded emission data be verified by an EU-accredited verifier. The verification covers: (1) completeness of emission sources reported; (2) accuracy of emission factors used; (3) boundary definition (direct vs indirect emissions); (4) data quality and audit trail. Indian mills exporting to the EU must engage a verification body accredited under ISO 14065, most of whom are based in Europe — adding verification costs of €5,000–15,000 per mill per year.","rejected":"CBAM has verification requirements to ensure emissions data is accurate. Third-party verification is needed."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"How does CBAM affect Indian stainless steel exports to the EU?","chosen":"Stainless steel (CN 7219–7220) is included in CBAM's scope from Phase 1. Stainless steel production has a fundamentally different emission profile from carbon steel: high-alloying elements, electric arc furnace dominance (lower emissions), and nickel/chromium inputs. The default emission value for stainless steel under CBAM is lower than for carbon steel BF-BOF routes. Indian stainless producers (Jindal Stainless being the largest) are predominantly EAF-based and thus better positioned for CBAM compliance.","rejected":"Indian stainless steel exporters are also affected by CBAM. The impact depends on their production methods and emission levels."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"What is the timeline for CBAM full implementation?","chosen":"CBAM timeline: October 2023 — transitional phase begins, reporting-only obligation for importers; December 2025 — transitional phase ends; January 2026 — full implementation begins, CBAM certificates required for imports; 2026–2034 — EU ETS free allowances for steel phased out in parallel with CBAM phase-in (preventing double protection). By 2034, the CBAM is fully effective as a border carbon adjustment.","rejected":"CBAM is being implemented in phases. Full implementation will require carbon payments for imported steel."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"How can Indian steel exporters prepare for CBAM?","chosen":"Preparation steps for Indian mills: (1) conduct ISO 14064-3 emission inventory for production units; (2) engage EU-accredited verifier for pre-assessment; (3) register in the EU CBAM registry via the authorised declarant in the EU; (4) evaluate investment in energy efficiency, renewable electricity procurement, scrap co-processing or H₂ injection to reduce measured intensity; (5) explore whether Indian carbon credit mechanisms (BEE PAT scheme) qualify as a carbon price that can be offset against CBAM.","rejected":"Indian steel exporters should take steps to understand and reduce their emissions to prepare for CBAM requirements."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"Does the EU's carbon border mechanism apply to steel rebar and long products?","chosen":"CBAM Phase 1 focuses primarily on carbon-intensive basic materials: iron and steel (CN 72), aluminium, cement, chemicals, hydrogen, and electricity. Certain downstream steel articles in CN 73 are included (e.g., tubes, pipes, hollow profiles). Rebar (CN 7214) and structural sections (CN 7216) used in construction are covered in CN 72 as primary steel, but processed construction products (pre-assembled structures) in CN 73 may have limited coverage. The full product scope is specified in Annex I of CBAM Regulation 2023/956.","rejected":"CBAM covers various steel products including both flat and long products, though the exact scope depends on the specific regulation."},
{"domain":"CBAM_COMPLIANCE","question":"What is the role of the authorised CBAM declarant?","chosen":"An authorised CBAM declarant is an entity registered in the EU that is responsible for purchasing CBAM certificates and filing the annual CBAM declaration on behalf of the importer. Declarants must be established in the EU and registered with the competent national authority. For Indian exporters, this means their EU-based customer or trading partner typically becomes the declarant — creating a new compliance burden in the EU import relationship that must be factored into commercial negotiations.","rejected":"The CBAM declarant is an EU-based entity responsible for CBAM compliance on behalf of the importer."},
# ── DATA_ANALYSIS / COMPARATIVE (10 pairs) ───────────────────────────────────
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"How has India's steel trade balance changed over FY2020–2025?","chosen":"India shifted from a net steel exporter in FY2021-22 (benefiting from post-COVID infrastructure demand) to a net importer in FY2024-25. Import volumes surged primarily in flat products — HR coils and CR coils — from China, Korea, and Japan, prompting multiple DGTR investigations. The flat steel trade deficit reached approximately Rs 28,000 crore in FY2025. India's total steel imports grew from 4.7 MT in FY2022 to 8.3 MT in FY2025.","rejected":"India's steel trade balance has fluctuated in recent years. The country has moved between net exporter and net importer status."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"What is the IS 2062 standard and what does it cover?","chosen":"IS 2062 is the Bureau of Indian Standards specification for hot rolled medium and high tensile structural steel. It covers five grades (E250 to E650) used in bridges, transmission towers, railway wagons, industrial structures, and shipbuilding. Under QCO 2024, both domestic manufacturers and importers must obtain BIS certification for IS 2062 compliant products before sale in India.","rejected":"IS 2062 is a BIS quality standard for structural steel used in construction and industrial applications."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"What are India's top steel export destinations by volume?","chosen":"India's top steel export destinations (FY2024-25 TRADESTAT data) are: UAE (largest, ~2.1 MT, re-exported to GCC), Nepal (~1.8 MT, primarily long products for construction), Italy (~0.8 MT, specialty grades), Bangladesh (~0.7 MT), Vietnam (~0.5 MT). Flat product exports go primarily to UAE and EU; long product exports go predominantly to South Asian neighbours. Exports to USA are constrained by Section 232 tariffs.","rejected":"India exports steel to various countries including neighbouring countries and Gulf states. The exact volumes vary by year and market conditions."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"How does India's steel capacity utilisation compare to China?","chosen":"India's steel capacity utilisation averaged approximately 82% in FY2024-25 — above the global average of 74%. China operates at approximately 65–68% utilisation on its 1.1 billion tonne capacity, creating approximately 350 million tonnes of idle capacity that drives export pressure when domestic demand softens. India's higher utilisation reflects tighter domestic supply-demand balance and is a key indicator of why Indian producers are genuinely injured by dumped imports.","rejected":"India's steel capacity utilisation rates differ from China's. China has excess capacity which contributes to low-price exports."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"What is the gravity model prediction for India-UAE steel trade?","chosen":"The gravity model (859 observations, 100 countries, FY2018–26; OLS in-sample R²=0.43, XGBoost leave-country-out CV R²≈0.27) predicts that a 5% UAE GDP growth would increase India-UAE flat steel trade by approximately 3.8%. With the CEPA RTA dummy active, the model shows an 18–22% structural uplift versus the no-FTA counterfactual, consistent with observed post-CEPA export increase from $0.8B to $1.2B.","rejected":"The gravity model suggests India-UAE steel trade will increase under CEPA. GDP growth in UAE also supports higher trade volumes."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"How do India's HR coil export prices compare to Chinese export prices?","chosen":"India's HR coil export price averaged $540–560/tonne FOB in FY2024-25. Chinese HR coil export prices have been $430–470/tonne — approximately $80–100/tonne below India's. This price gap reflects China's excess capacity and state subsidy base, and is the central evidence supporting anti-dumping and safeguard investigations by importing countries. For India to compete in third markets, the gap needs to narrow through production efficiency gains or be offset by CBAM levies on Chinese exports to the EU.","rejected":"Indian and Chinese steel prices differ significantly. China generally exports at lower prices which affects competition in global markets."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"What is India's revealed comparative advantage in steel products?","chosen":"India has a positive Revealed Comparative Advantage (RCA > 1) in long products — rebars, wire rods, structural sections — driven by abundant iron ore, strong domestic construction demand creating scale, and competitive labour costs in fabrication. India's RCA in flat products (HR coil, CR coil, coated steel) is below 1, reflecting the quality and specification gaps versus Korean and Japanese producers. This bifurcation shapes the appropriate export strategy: defend flat product positions in regional markets while building flat product quality for export premium.","rejected":"India has competitive advantages in some steel products but not others. This reflects the structure of India's steel industry and resource base."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"What is the impact of Chinese steel capacity on global steel prices?","chosen":"China produces approximately 55% of global crude steel output. When Chinese domestic demand weakens (as in the 2023–25 property sector downturn), excess production is exported at sub-market prices — the 2024 surge in Chinese steel exports to 110 million tonnes (highest since 2015) depressed global HRC prices by approximately 20–25%. This transmission mechanism is why Indian anti-dumping cases against China have accelerated: Chinese domestic demand contraction directly results in Indian import injury.","rejected":"China's large steel production affects global prices. When China has excess production, it exports more which can lower global prices."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"How does India's steel consumption per capita compare to global benchmarks?","chosen":"India's steel consumption per capita was approximately 97 kg in FY2024-25 — below the global average of 233 kg/person and far below China (560 kg) and South Korea (1,150 kg). The National Steel Policy targets 160 kg per capita by 2030, implying approximately 90 MT additional demand from per-capita convergence alone. This consumption headroom is the fundamental demand driver underpinning India's long-term capacity expansion investment thesis.","rejected":"India's steel consumption per capita is below global averages, suggesting significant room for growth as the economy develops."},
{"domain":"DATA_ANALYSIS","question":"What is the relationship between India's infrastructure spending and steel demand?","chosen":"Infrastructure (roads, railways, housing, power) accounts for approximately 55–60% of India's steel consumption. The government's Rs 11.1 lakh crore capital expenditure in Union Budget 2024-25 — with Railways (Rs 2.55 lakh crore), PMGSY roads, and PMAY housing driving structural steel demand — creates a direct steel demand multiplier. Each Rs 1 lakh crore of infrastructure spend generates approximately 1.2–1.5 MT of incremental steel demand based on sector mix.","rejected":"India's infrastructure development plans create significant steel demand. Government spending on roads, railways and housing increases steel consumption."},
]

